To style the `<button>` elements in your web app, you can use CSS to apply various styles and formatting to the text, background color, and border of the button.

Here is an example of how you can style the text of a button using CSS:
```
.button {
  background-color: #4CAF50;
  color: white;
  padding: 16px 32px;
  border: none;
  text-align: center;
  text-shadow: 0 1px 1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.0);
  border-radius: 4px;
  font-size: 16px;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: 0.3s ease-in-out;
}

.button:hover {
  background-color: #b7d9c8;
  color: #263441;
}
```
This code defines a CSS class called `.button` that is applied to a `<button>` element. It sets the background color, text color, padding, border, and text shadow to `#4CAF50`, a dark blue color. The `:hover` rule sets the background color and text color to `#b7d9c8`, a lighter blue color when the button is being hovered over.

You can then use this CSS class in your JavaScript to style the button text as desired:
```
<button class="button">Button Text</button>
```
You can use this CSS class on any kind of element that you want to apply this styling to, such as `<a>` elements, `<input>` elements, or `<select>` elements.

Here is an example of how you can style the background color of a button:
```
.button:hover {
  background-color: #b7d9c8;
}
```
This code sets the background color to `#b7d9c8`, a lighter blue color when the button is being hovered over.

You can also use CSS to style the border of a button:
```
.button {
  border-color: #4CAF50;
  color: white;
  padding: 16px 32px;
}

.button:hover {
  border-color: #b7d9c8;
}

