You can define your schema.json file in your project root directory, but it's a good idea to organize it by structure and layers, as I mentioned earlier. Here's an example structure for a Gatsby project with multiple pages, with the schema.json file defined in the pages directory:

pages/
  index.js
  about.js
  contacts.js
  settings.js
  api.js
schema.json
  -- contains the schema.json file
  -- contains the GraphQL schema for pages
  -- contains the resolvers for the pages' CRUD endpoints
  -- contains the types for the pages' data fields
```json
{
  "pages": {
    "index": {
      "pages": {
        "index": {
          "components": {
            "Home": {
              "id": "Home",
              "name": "Home",
              "type": "Page"
            },
            "About": {
              "id": "About",
              "name": "About",
              "type": "Page"
            },
            "Contacts": {
              "id": "Contacts",
              "name": "Contacts",
              "type": "Page"
            },
            "Settings": {
              "id": "Settings",
              "name": "Settings",
              "type": "Page"
            },
            "API": {
              "id": "API",
              "name": "API",
              "type": "Page"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
In this structure, the pages directory contains the different pages and their CRUD endpoints, while the schema.json file contains the GraphQL schema for each page. This way, you can reuse the same schema for all your pages and customize it according to your needs.

Please note that this is just an example and you may need to adjust it to fit your specific needs. Also, please be sure to double-check the information provided by Gatsby's documentation and the code examples provided by the Gatsby team.

