Unary ++ operator is an operator that increments the value of its right operand. It is similar to the ++ operator in C++ but it is not part of the C++ standard library.

The following code example shows how to use unary ++ operator in printf statements:
```
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int x = 5;

    std::cout << "x = " << x << ", unary ++: " << ++x << std::endl; // x = 5, 6, unary ++: 6, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 5

    std::cout << "x = " << x << ", unary ++: " << ++x << std::endl; // x = 7, 6, unary ++: 7, 7, 7, 7, 5

    return 0;
}
```
In the first printf statement, the unary ++ operator is used to increment the value of the x variable by 1. The output shows that the value of x is increased by 1 and then printed to the console.

In the second printf statement, the unary ++ operator is used to increment the value of x by 1. The output shows that the value of x is incremented by 1 and then printed to the console.

In both cases, the value of x is printed to the console before the unary ++ operator is applied. Therefore, it is not possible to use unary ++ operator in printf statements to print the value of a variable in a specific order.

